Right now, most agent memory is centralized. Your Claude Code session, your reasoning idea, your notes in someone else's cloud — you don't fully own them. You co-own them with the platform. And we all know what happens when privacy is an afterthought.

As an AI x web3 builder, I often face the issue about a trilemma: sovereignty, memory, and cost. It is either store everything forever and you bleed money. Keep it cheap in a vendor database and you don't own it. Put it on-chain raw and it's slow and expensive.

I built Cortex — an AI memory layer on Arkiv that pushes on all three. Own by your wallet. Arkiv actually have the mechanism that makes memory fade like human. What you ignore fades, what you cite stays.
Memories that behave like human memory. Also I've introduce RaBitQ algorithm to help in compresses embeddings to make memory store onchain practical,it is about thirty-one times of the orginal size.


